<div id="review_3195568368" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3195568368" />
    <a title="Clovis Ong" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/36809154-clovis-ong"><img alt="Clovis Ong" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1581243371p2/36809154.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3195568368?book_show_action=true">Mar 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Clovis Ong" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Clovis Ong" href="/user/show/36809154-clovis-ong">Clovis Ong</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3195568368" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1283577341219081018">In terms of power proportion of beings such as the Adeptus Astartes, Wraight nails it. Some writers, like Abnett, depict them as almost too overpowered. Others like Thorpe and McNeill make them seem so vastly underpowered to the point of ludicrousness. Wraight gets this balance right - Space Marines are not quite demigods, but close. Primarchs are not quite gods, but close, and definitely more powerful than demigods. I like that balance. It feels restrained and correct for this universe. <br/><br/>That le</span>
  <span id="freeText1283577341219081018" style="display:none">In terms of power proportion of beings such as the Adeptus Astartes, Wraight nails it. Some writers, like Abnett, depict them as almost too overpowered. Others like Thorpe and McNeill make them seem so vastly underpowered to the point of ludicrousness. Wraight gets this balance right - Space Marines are not quite demigods, but close. Primarchs are not quite gods, but close, and definitely more powerful than demigods. I like that balance. It feels restrained and correct for this universe. <br /><br />That level of world building, and an interesting (albeit predictable) story structure, win points for this novel. We see interesting arcs - the primarch of the White Scars undertakes a journey that transforms him from indecisiveness to forceful action. We see a simple but nicely layered thematic motif of brother versus brother combat on a legion level, juxtaposed with primarch combat in godlike showdowns, both crosscut simultaneously to engaging effect. Not transcendent material by a long shot, but a worthy effort. </span>
  <a data-text-id="1283577341219081018" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


